deck_description: Here is an OTK  deck where the gameplay consist to Simply spam special summons of Blackwing monsters to play beatsticks like Borrelsword and take the duel in one turn. If you play first you can relieve on the raidraptor link to play the xyz 4 strix, tuto a rank-up and make a board with Armor Master and Cyber Dragon Infinity. The xyz 6 raidraptor is an alternative if you triggered effects that prevent you to summon non-winged beasts monsters, as it can destroy a monster and burn the opponent to facilitate the OTK.  The ideal starter is Simoon The Poison Wing + Steam The Cloak. Simoon banish Steam and tuto Black Whirlwind to search Auster the South Wind. Normal summon Auster to special summon Steam and tuto another Blackwing monster, now with litteraly one card you can spam the board.  Zephyros The Elite is an important card since you can search it during the raidraptor loop to bounce back a Black Whirlwind and have one more special summon.  Auster is important too but 1 is sufficient, it's relatively easy to tuto and more could be bricky.

deck_name: TRAPTRIX VS ALL META Post Battles of Legend Hero's Revenge 2019
deck_description: YOUTUBE LINK - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ro5o6N8JbfU&feature=youtu.be

I changed a lot of things just to go further on this deck. First of all, its only focused on the pot this time to make the deck faster. Krawlers on the GY is a need to the forbidden combo.  
  • Deus X-Krawler is still the main priority, you can't hold the game without it.  I put magical merchant for send monsters to GY  giving you a spell/trap.
 
  • World Legacy Survivor will send 4 cards to the GY to give you a world legacy or Krawler card, this will make easier to send many krawlers as possible to flip-down monsters. If any important monster was sent to the GY, you can use Monster Reincarnation. When you use it, Discart krawlers, Tindangle Intruder or World Legacy's Mind Meld keeping your World Legacy Pawns in work to flip-down.
 
  • The main mechanic of bring Pot of the Forbidden and Deus X-Krawler is the same, try to link flip monsters to get Subterror Behemoth Fiendess. Flip a monster on his zone and get pot of the forbidden. Activate fiendess effect sending Tindangle Intruder to the GY and special summoning the pot. Or send deus x-krawler to the GY, flip Krawler Glial on his zone, special summon deus krawler from your GY and Pot from your hand or banish Mind Meld from your GY and special summon Deus krawler, flip it face-up with pawns, get the pot and activate fiendess effect.
  Sometimes this deck is slow depending on the beginning hand, but if you have mind meld and a krawler, half of the objective is done. The link krawlers is for rule 3.

deck_excerpt: All noteworthy Dragon cards most of which got enabled by the recent Dragon Links. Here you can find bunch of techs / engines / dragon cards which migh
deck_description:
Hi I am Poske Yugituber. I thoroughly isolated dragons with zero potentional from the good Dragons. This is a great place to come by if you are searching for Dragon techs / engines / decks. Each Dragon / Dragon related Card has its usability  explained below but first here are some diff decks in which I exploited Dragons. Some decks which can use Guardragons / Dragon toolbox for powerful combos:
  • Dragunity (Leyvaten and Barcha became good) - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=C2E3CzKyC_k
  • Pendulum magician variants - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eOzjmxi0eac&t=
  • Crusadia - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TUJ5Q57Byms
  • Rokkets with Striker Dragon - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BbauQlvSm0w
  • Thunder - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ELtj-c_iysI
  • Rose Dragons https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PGK_WQ4EHjo&t=35s (No guardragon, fresh)
  • Buster blader, Cyber Darks, Heraldics, Hieratics, Red-Eyes, Blue-Eyes, World chalice.
  Guardragon database download links: (2 because 1 wasn't enough) but I recommend reading each dragon card below if you are in a hunt for good dragons. https://www.sendspace.com/file/ge6xgp https://www.sendspace.com/file/plj4pw NEW Garden Rose Maiden - not a dragon but can revive Dragon synchros NEW! Nebula the Star Cloud Dragon - summons itself and a lvl 8 dragon from hand , adds back lvl 4 dragons from grave. New! Spiral Dragon Bulge - You can special summon him from hand/grave if you control 2 or more Light and or Dark dragons. He is level 8 and can make all monsters become lvl 8. R8 plays for days.

Odd-Eyes Revolution Dragon - in scale he revives a Dragon Fusion / Synchro / Xyz He also searches Pendulum dragons, Darkwurm being the most relevant one Red-Eyes Darkness Metal Dragon - doesn't really need an introduction, revives dragons commonly summoned off guardragons. The most popular dragon. not HOPT. Chaos Emperor Dragon - Envoy of the End - Got an errata, searchable by Melody of awakening Dragon just like his new brother below, He is more of a backup plan Chaos Emperor, the Dragon of Armageddon - his pendulum effect allows you to fetch banished dragons by destroying itself, Eclipse Wyvern is often re-used with him He also has massive removal effect (Send based) but you gotta sacrifice the field on your own except for the Extra monster zone. Divine Dragon Lord Felgrand - Versitaile Removal if revived from graveyard, Can revive a lvl 7/8 Dragon-Type monster if he destroys a monster by battle Light and Darkness Dragon - He is one of the best tribute summons in the game. Once per chain when an effect is activated he can negate it by reducing his attack by 500 Given that he isn't once per turn and has 2800 atk. Thats a lot of negates if you can protect him from getting ran over. Amorphage Goliath - Restricts summoning from the extra deck, often brought out with hieratic link during the Opp turn. Chaos Dragon Levianeer - sort of outclasses other Chaos monsters as he can be brought out even if you only have lights / darks in grave. Revives a monster in def if you only use lights, pops 2 if you use both attributes, Shuffles a random card from the opp if you. This card is really popular. Searchable by melody just like his handloop brother below Darkest Diabolos, Lord of t he Lair - if a Dark monster is tributed, (Dark thunder dragon for thunder dragon Collosus for example) he can special summon himself from the hand / graveyard even if he was not originaly there the excact moment dark monster was tributed. He can tribute 1 dark monster (including itself) to make Opp place 1 card from their hand on top of their deck. Another quite popular card Mythic Water Dragon - If you control an earth monster you can special summon him, that is all. he is level 8 water dragon. Not really utilized anywhere since D- ruler ban Destrudo the Lost Dragon's Frisson - He can summon himself from the hand/grave by reducing his own level so that the combined level of him and the monster he targeted is 7. Due to that he often becomes a low level dragon so you can access Guardragons with him. Best of all he is a tuner, easy high lvl synchros. Super popular card Arkbrave Dragon - Back in the days when Dark Matter Dragon was legal, he was how people used to drop the Amorphage Goliath on their Opp Dark Armed Dragon - Kinda outclassed by Levianeer nowdays as he requires specifically 3 Dark monsters in the graveyard. he can banish a dark monster to pop a card that is not once per turn so he can essentially pop a bunch of times, just keep putting darks in the graveyard. Eventho this card was F&L list it really ain't that scarry Dark Armed, the Dragon of Annihilation - If you have exactly 5 dark monsters in your graveyard you can use 1 level 5 or Higher dark Dragon to summon him. Can Pop a lot of cards Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay - a handtrap dragon which helps you fix your hands as well as somewhat protecting your field from targeting when you go off. Popular Mana Dragon Zirnitron - Often played in Red-Eyes backrow decks. as they can easly drop him in the graveyard with Red-Eyes fusion infact he is their best target for Meteor Black Comet Dragon. Sometimes you see him teched by dark magician players to Linkbelt Wall Dragon - a free dragon drop but importantly he sort of restricts both players from summoning low link rating monsters. Lightpulsar dragon - Typical chaos summoning mechanic, revives a level 5 or higher Dark Dragon - type monster when he is sent from the field to the graveyard. Redmd, Diabolos and Aether, the Evil Empowering Dragon are probably your best targets to revive of him. Speaking of Aether he is easly the BEST CARD to summon of Hieratic link Darkflare Dragon - Chaos Dragon which foolishes Dragons by sending dragons from hand then he can also banish any card in either Graveyard. MASSIVE potentional now that Galaxy-Eyes Dark Matter Dragon is banned as he was inhibiting Konami from printing Dragons which are worth foolishing for the most part Instant fusion - into Darkfire dragon. Free lvl 4 dark dragon drop. Odd-Eyes Persona Dragon - Look you either summon Aether, Amorphage monsters or this card via hieratic link. He can negate the effect of a monster special summoned from the extra deck. Background Dragon - IF you control no cards he can revive himself from the graveyard as well as summon a level 4 or lower dragon from the hand AKA easy Dragon links. Best when combined with bunch of foolish cards in pure dragon decks such as rokkets. Starliege Dragon Seyfert - Often summoned via Elpy. Can send a dragon from hand or field (Idealy Eclipse Wyvern) to search a same leveled Dragon. He can send itself to search the "mini chaos dragons" which I ll talk about next Black Dragon Collapserpent - He can easly help you do the whole Guardragon combo. Special summons himself by banishing a light monster then he float searches his brother below which does the opposite White Dragon Wyverburster. Banish a dark Drop him, search his brother above if sent to the graveyard. Elpy Pisty Explode etc. Both are super popular Dragons Eclipse Wyvern - banishes a dragon when sen't to the graveyard, adds the dragon to the hand when banished. not once per turn often looped with Pisty Guardragon Rokket Tracer - the best target for Rokket quick launch as well as 2 dragons in one for the rokket archetype. He is just a an easy lvl 4 dragon tuner which you can ss via Quick Launch and at that point start climbing.. do something like Boreload Savage Dragon Storm Dragon - If you control a spellcaster you can drop him on the field. He is fantastic in Crusadia as their link 1 and reclusia are both spellcasters and Crusadia has an unique approach to Guardragon combos as their link2 moves zones setting up Elpy / Pisty Crusadia Draco - searchable of Crusadia link 1. The reason why Crusadia is one of the best decks for creating Massive locks via Guardragons Supreme King Dragon Darkwurm - 1 card full scale which is relevant in rokkets, other then that one of the most popular dragons as he can revive himself giving you a plus if you decide to run gate zero. Gateway Dragon - He can SS himself if your Opp controls a monster and then you can special summon 1 levle 4 or lower Dark draogn from the hand. Overall he is one card link 2 dragon if you will. Decent going second side option if you want to accelerate your deck Iron Dragon Tiamaton - If 3 cards are in the same Column which you can do by yourself you can drop him anywhere then destroy all cards in its Column. Doesn't really go well with Dragon decks atm, as they don't fill up S/T for the most part but he found its place in many other decks. Koa'ki Meiru Drago - he restricts everyone from summoning Light / Dark monsters. All you have to do is reveal a Dragon in each endphase so that he doesnt self destruct. Put him in Dragunity, summon of Elpy easy lock for Dark / light decks Keeper of the Shrine - He summons himself from the hand / grave when a dragon anywhere is sent to the graveyard by card effect or destroyed. he is 2 tributes for dragons. he can add back Normal Dragons if they were the ones destroyed. Good card but struggling to find its home atm. Draconnet - summon a vannila dragon such as galaxy searpent. Enter Ib the World Chalice Miko, do the whole guardragon combo. Searchable by Cynet Mining so you can run 6. Not a dragon but does a lot for dragons, popular in general Defrag Dragon - Sort of like A Danger! Version of Dragons, good card sometimes finds its way to good decks Debris Dragon - When Normal summoned Can revive one sub 500 atk monster. If he revives a dragon you could there you go 2 dragons of 1 normal summon. Influence Dragon - lvl 3 tuner. can turn any monster into a dragon Hibernation Dragon. If he is Normal / SS you can add level 4 or lower dragon to the hand If you don't control the link except the turn he was sent to the Gy he can revive Dark dragon Link monsters. Huge potentional but slow card Ultimaya Tzolkin - Outdated Agarpain if you will altho quite toolboxy might see more play in a future kinda hard to abuse atm. Keep in mind he can even be triggered  by something like Dust Tornado on Opp turn Hardened Armed Dragon - can summon himself by sending high level 8+ monster to the graveyard. Sees no play atm but there is some potentional Triggering wurm - if link summoned for link monster revive it under link marker. then it can't be used for more link summoning. gives you a draw + if you poped or banished by a link monster. Idk sounds interesting but nothing groundbreaking tbh Soldier Dragon. Once per turn if Opp actives a card or an effect (quick) you can special summon lvl 2 or lower dragon from the deck. Not viable atm but if we get some good low lvl dragons which can act as removal he could get summoned of hieratic link, if protected by something like Titanic he wouldn't be a bad choise Omni Dragon Brotaur - second most summoned dragon off Elpy, discards a card targets a monster on the field searches another monster of the same attribute and type.   Dragon Rulers - ll Say what they do if they become legal not to waste people time Unexpected dai - summons galaxy searpent for example. Goo link climbing Accelight - again summons galaxy searpent, heavy restriction but it won't matter in some decks. Return of the Dragon Lords - revives lvl 7 and 8 dragons as well as offering generic protection Cards of Consonance - discard a sub 1000 atk Dragon tuner draw 2 cards World Legacy Guardragon - Hi IB, revives Dragons, moves them sets up guardragons well Dragon Shrine - HOPT foolish burial for dragons. Darkwurm, Background dragon and destrudo. The King of D - discard a spell / trap. Search Melody, Flute or Rhapsody. (not popular engine) Melody of Awakening Dragon - can search many Chaos Dragons as well as blue eyes, easy Blue-Eyes Alternative Dragon drop The flute of Summoning Dragon - if you control a King of D and you prob do. activate it to summon up to 2 dragons from hand. Dragon Revival Rhapsody - if you control a spellcaster target up to 2 dragons atleast 1 Normal monster and revive them. Conditional but revives 2 dragons Quick Launch - summons a rokket from the deck. Rokkets are dragons often times tuners Dragunity Divine Lance - can be used as an engine with Romulus and phalanx Dragon ravine - searchable by romulus costly "Dragon Shrine" often played in pendulum guardragon decks Trade in - the Dragon is on the picture, discard a level 8 monster draw 2 cards Dragunity Phalanx - engine with Dragunity Romulus for more dragon drops Odd Eyes Fusion - great fusion card for Dragons. Fuses from hand and field or extra deck when going second. Odd Eyes Vortext Dragon is a common target Dragon's Mirror - fantastic fusion card for dragons. Fuses from hand and grave. Most popular target is Borreload Furious Dragon Dragoncaller Magician - turns monsters in dragons when in scale, searchable with pend call, duelist alience, wisdom eye. Allows magicians to do guardragon combos. Darkwurm helps to ;) Dragon's Bind - wierd Vanity Emptiness Esque Trap card for High attack dragons. Hot Red Dragon Archfiend Abyss - often summoned of Agarpain. Negates a card revives a tuner when he inflicts dmg. Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon - often summoned of Agarpain. negates monster effects can get big in multiple ways. Dragunity Knight Gae Dearg - summoned of Agarpain in dragunity deck for most combos. He can search level 4 or lower dragon and winged beast monster important one being zepyhros for more Redmd loops. Just a powerful accelarator which is no longer Dragunity Exclusive due to Agarpain Ib the world chalice Miko - again not a dragon but insane card for accelerating guardragons Hieratic Dragon King of Atum - summons a dragon from the deck, elpy does that to tho so he is quite unpopular atm Queen Dragon Djinn - R4 battle protection for dragons, revives lvl 5 + dragons Twin Triangle Dragon - link 2 accessed with low lvl dragons summons high lvl dragons but negates their effects and restricts their attacks. Saryuja - people often use their guardragons to summon this because while Guardragons are on the field you can only summon Dragons and this way you go around that Darkness Metal, the Dragon of Dark Steel - Revives a dead / banished dragon negates its effects also you can't ss link monsters if you do that. Three Burst Dragon - can negate battle tricks in a dmg step, piercing dmg. Has a powerful next turn effect but honestly he is summoned just for arrows and link rating All the cards below require atleast 2 link pointers on an empty space Agarpain the Guardragon - Summons dragons from the extra deck Elpy the Guardragon - Summons dragons from the hand or deck (In danger of banlist) Pisty the Guardragon - Summons dead or banished dragons Hieratic Seal of the Heavenly Spheres - 2 Disruptions in one due to Aether (My favorite target). Dragunity Knight - Romulus - just a good Dragon extender Borreload dragon - can be summoned of Agarpain which is huge Borrelsword dragon - can be summoned of Agarpain ;) Borrelguard dragon - not as good as his brothers but I wanted to mention him Duel Link Dragon - wanna be tzolkin it is really hard to abuse this card tbh Armiryle the Starguide Dragon - can help you summon monsters from hand. Dragon so you can use guardragons to go into him. Naturia Barkion - yep thats a dragon ;). Rip trap based decks. Supperalloy Beast Raptinus - yep thats a dragon to. enables gemini monsters hi gigaplant

deck_excerpt: Effect damage. Battle damage is the last resort in this deck.
deck_description: Really straightforward. Vijam is your key card. Normal Summon it or Special Summon it via reasoning. Then tribute it for geira guile. Duza acts as a graveyard set up by sending a vijam to the GY, then geira guile or dark garnex can SS 2 vijams instead of 1 from the gy. Cubic traps and spells help disable monsters by placing cubic counters on them, making them useless. Also Mask of Restrict stop your opponent from doing Anything. It won't effect you as the cubic monster SEND the to GY to SS themselves. Twin twisters, back row removal. The reason I didn't add more back row removal is because most of the cubic monsters in this deck deal effect damage. Btw I don't recomment summoning Crimson Nova to slowly burn you and your opponent. I only summon it in desperate situations. Which are few because in most cases, your field consists of low-attack monsters and your opponent has high attack monsters. Then you draw Crimson Nova, then it's useless unless you have 3 other cubic monsters with DIFFERENT Names. So Crimson Nova is basically used for fusion Summoning. Also Linkuribo with vijam just in case.

deck_name: Black Luster and Gaia Chaos Army
deck_description: Just For Fun
1. All or nothing

So I've never posted a Chain Burn deck profile before because I either haven't had time or was focused on posting more meta based decks for you guys like Sky Striker and such, but now I will post this deck up for those of you who love Classic Chain Burn (Without Mystic Mine because the deck does fine without it). Chain Burn has been around for forever and has progressed as different cards have come along in Yugioh. This build I have been testing, from scratch of course, did very well in testing and has a low brick rate. And yes, this deck is for competitive use just like all the other decks I post! I have some very spicy techs for you guys that I alone. have come up with that no one knows about... The first one is abusing Dimensional Fissure and Macro Cosmos. The fact that Orcust, Sky Striker, Danger Thunder are a thing in this meta is a serious problem. To solve this problem, resolving one of these two cards could mean the end of the game for an Orcust or Sky Striker player. Banishing everything in their graveyard really hurts. And sure they can go into Knightmare Phoenix and just pop it but it should at least buy you a turn or two. The way to use Macro Cosmos properly is to flip it when your opponent goes to use a card that sends a card to the graveyard like Knightmare Mermaid, that way it will be banished instead which would kill their Orcust combo for the most part, forcing them to change their plans. And honestly, Chain Burn could care less if their monsters, spells and traps get banished. For the extra deck some of you might be confused, but they are all just Waking The Dragon targets. Clara & Ruska is to out Secret Village of The Spellcasters. Since I play Pot of Extravagance, it is important that the extra deck has two or three of every important card, most importantly, Raidraptor - Ultimate Falcon. Falcon is almost impossible to get over and they are forced to make weird plays to go into Borrelsword or something with higher attack than 3500 to out it. Now for the other spicy techs... Those are in the side deck. Firstly, I want to introduce Volcanic Queen with Soul of Fire. Why play kaijus when we can play this nasty package? Volcanic Queen literally threatens you in the card text saying "During your End Phase, either Tribute 1 other monster or take 1000 damage." That's kinda a scary threat consider we're playing Chain Burn and to a Sky Striker player, summoning this card can be harmful since they cannot activate cards like Engage or any deck that is effected by kaijus. Now, the whole idea behind Soul of Fire is being able to inflict 1250 to your opponent and banishing a Volcanic Queen from your deck, which is a lot of damage. Also allowing your opponent to draw a card is a good thing because it just means more damage towards Secret Barrel and the other burn cards. My other spicy tech is Timidity. When you know your opponent is siding in Twin Twisters or any backrow removal, just side these bad boys in and your opponent will have no idea what hit them when you chain everything during your opponents turn and they can't destroy them when they are set. Lastly, I want to mention that yes Ash is a threat to this deck, but in order to win vs Ash you just bait it. For example if you have Pot of Duality and Card of Demise in hand you would want to set the Demise and activate the Duality, forcing them to negate it with Ash because they think you are desperate for a card since its the only card in your hand. But after they negate it just flip Demise and draw 3. I hope you guys enjoy this deck profile and stick around for more!

deck_excerpt: Altergeist Deck • Control • Snowball pace • Trap centric
deck_description: The goal of an Altergeist Deck is to snowball as quickly as possible; so as to be oppressive as early as possible.  Key cards in successfully employing the oppressive Altergeist strategy include:  • Multifaker: It can bring out Silq for a free bounce, it can bring out Meluseek to set up your next turn (can be used as Link fodder on your next turn or popped during your opponent's turn by the likes of Hexstia or Protocol for a search) / bring out removal, or it can bring out Kunqueary for an impermanence-esque effect.  • Hexstia: It can serve as a trap / spell negate which is significant in this day and age with Striker, Orcust and Salamangreat having powerful spell/trap cards.  • Protocol: It can serve as a negate, and can set up your future turns by activating the floating effects of Hexstia and Meluseek.  With the Altergeist strategy core being discussed, it is important to understand that the best way to play altergeist is to accentuate the strengths of this strategy; the ability to prevent the opponent from making meaningful progress (through a variety of negation, bounce and removal effects). Hand-traps, consistency boosters (draw cards) and traps that can play against the opponent whilst powering multifaker are all good choices. So, without further ado, we'll now discuss the cards that aid this strategy - from this decklist.  • Most of the traps in this lineup either boost the consistency of the altergeist strategy (spoofing, manifestation), are part of the core strategy (protocol) or aid in the oppression. The traps that aid in the oppression that Altergeist is known for are all, for the most part, able to be trap tricked - which helps increase the pace of this deck by giving it immediate answers to an opponent via trap trick. Trap trick, in this deck, can setup Secret Village of the Spellcasters to shut down a Sky Striker player... it can bring out Magic Deflector to shut down a field spell like The Hidden City... it can bring out a heavy storm duster to blow back the mirror match or to prevent any backrow setup by another deck... and lastly it can bring out an impermanence for a monster effect negate.  • The hand traps in this decklist are all there to prevent the opponent from gaining an advantage. Gnomaterial is significant in that it can shut down most T1 decks early on, while Ash & Ogre hit a variety of strategies with the negation / destruction they threaten. D.D. crow in the side & Phantazmay allow the deck to be more versatile going 2nd; potentially hitting GY targets for GY centric decks with D.D. Crow, and potentially seeing more hand traps with Phantazmay.  • Secret Village can be replaced with Necro Valley (just 1 necro valley + 2 secret village is fine too); both of these field spells hit strong meta-strategies incredibly hard.

deck_excerpt: The definitive guide to playing Tindangles.
deck_description:
After countless hours, I have finally managed to put together the best solution to playing pure Tindangles. So sit back, relax, and read this guide if you ever wanted to learn how to play this deck. When playing Tindangles, it is best to think of your entire deck as consisting of trap cards. Since your monsters are mainly flip monsters, they will usually have to remain face down for a turn if you want their effects to go off. What this usually means is that you need to be thinking one step ahead of your opponent and taking into account which cards on your field they are most likely to destroy, which leads us to the next point. The Graveyard: Tindangles benefit heavily from being in the graveyard as their trap, Tindangle Delaunay, can be banished to immediately summon three to your field face down. That being said, there are some things to keep in mind when playing around with your graveyard:
  1. Always try and dump Tindangle Delaunay or Nagel's protection with Foolish Burial Goods into the graveyard to set up plays for later or get protection for your monsters on the field respectively.
  2. Try and always keep Tindangle Intruder and Tindangle Apostle in the graveyard. Intruder summons itself from the GY if another monster is special summoned face down, and Apostle will allow you to get some crazy draw power the turn you flip it up after summoning it back to the field using Delaunay.
The hand: There are also some things to keep in mind with the cards you want in your hand. Most of the time you always want to set Tindangle Angel or Tindangle Trinity as they are your big combo starters and allow the deck to start chugging along. Tindangle Base Gardna often ends up as a brick so try and keep it in the deck or graveyard as much as possible. Tindangle Hound is the odd one out as you should keep it in your hand if you have an Angel set, otherwise, keep it in the GY as often as possible. The Strategy: This deck is often very slow to get started, but once you have several copies of Delaunay in the GY it can be extremely hard to stop. Always start your turn either setting Angel or Trinity and try to keep their defense bolstered with Nagel's Protection. If Nagel's ends up getting destroyed, don't worry, its Graveyard effect lets you add another copy of itself to your hand, as well as discard a Tindangle card to the GY. If you do not have a monster to set, it is best to stall using Needlebug Nest to try and dump three Tindangles and a Delaunay to summon them on your opponent's turn and keep drawing and discarding cards using Hand Destruction. If you need to stall even further, you can often cripple your opponent early with a well timed Solemn Strike or Warning. Once you have the resources, you want to summon Tindangle Acute Cerberus (preferably with a Trinity as a material as it will allow you to add a Gergonne's End to your hand for some extra protection and dump a Delaunay in the GY in case Cerberus dies. On another note, you must also use Base Gardna as a material or else Cerberus will not gain any attack points). With such a huge monster on the field and the multiple layers of defense you will have in case it somehow dies, you are pretty much free to continue attacking for game. Also make sure to use the rest of your Extra Deck as a toolbox for various situations you may encounter.

deck_description: Yami Marik runs an Immortality-Torture Deck, which focuses on slowly torturing his opponents and watching them squirm. In the theme of pain Yami Marik's cards slowly drain an opponent's strength, such as discarding their hand with "Helpoemer" and "Crush Card Virus"and lowering ATK with "Dark Jeroid". Some of his cards, like "Nightmare Wheel" and "Viser Des", are based on torture machines. Yami Marik's Deck otherwise relies on a variety of powerful Trap Cards and Fiend-Type monsters.

deck_excerpt: Its all about flipping and flipping off your opponent.
deck_description:
Deck Created By: Big Crunch/1 (Deck Inspiration: ???) *Updated Deck* Goal: Summon Tarotrei and use the flips for advantage Monsters
  • Prediction Princess Tarotrei - Its your main boss monster. Summon it as much as possible.
  • Prediction Princess Coinorma - *Flip* It's Tarotrei's companion. It searches most of your flips. It can also act as a triple wall. Use it alongside Tarotrei.
  • Impcantation Cards - Provides you searching and recovery with your Ritual cards.
  • Guard Dog - *Flip* Good first target for Coinorma. Prevents your opponent from Special Summoning.
  • Deus X-Krawler - *Flip* Another good first target for Coinorma. Negates your opponent's monster effects on the field. (Can be switched with General Raiho or Plasma).
  • Pot of the Forbidden - *Flip* It has 4 uses depending on the situation
  • Subterror Behemoth Phospheroglacier - *Flip* It dumps 1 card from your deck for any situation needed.
  • Invader of the Throne - *Flip* Allows you to steal 1 monster from your opponent (Can be switched with any card you want) (Good replacements who does the same job: Hade-Hane, Penguin Soldier, Subterror Behemoth Umastryx)
  • Tindangle Angel - *Flip* Allows you to summon 1 Flip card from your hand or graveyard, also it stops your opponent's Battle Phase.
  • Magician of Faith - *Flip* Allows you to recover 1 Spell card from your graveyard.
  • Scapeghost - *Flip* Allows you access to Links and Synchros by summoning tokens and being a tuner.
  • Exodius the Ultimate Forbidden Lord - Allows you to shuffle your monsters from the graveyard into the deck for recycling or deckout prevention. It also allows you to send 1 monster from your deck if you attack with it.
  • The Winged Dragon of Ra - Sphere Mode - gives you a pretty effective removal of monsters. (Good replacements who does the same job: Kaijus, Lava Golem)
  • Jinzo - It prevents from using Traps. (Good replacements who does the same job: Royal Decree, Denko Sekka)
  • Spell Canceller - It prevents from using Spells. Use it carefully. (Good replacements who does the same job: Imperial Order, Horus the Black Flame Dragon LV8)
  • Manju of the Ten Thousand Hands - It searches your Ritual cards. (It can also be replaced by the Prediction Princess flip cards, if you want)
Spells
  • Pre-Preparation of Rites - Allows you to search both the Ritual Monster and Spell.
  • Monster Reborn - Revive a monster from either player's graveyard. (Can be replaced with any card you want)
  • Reasoning - Allows you to summon a monster that can be Normal Summoned from your deck, provided that your opponent guessed wrong. (Can be replaced with any card you want)
  • Prediction Ritual - Allows you summon Tarotrei. It also searches another copy of Tarotrei or Coinorma by banishing it.
  • Shared Ride - You can use it during your opponent's turn to gain advantage. (Can be replaced with any card you want)
  • Legacy of the Duelist - Allows you to recover 1 monster from your Graveyard in exchange of your Draw Phase. It prevents Extra Deck monsters from attacking during summon. It can destroy your opponent's backrow by negating your attack. It also prevents setting 2 backrow cards from the hand.
  Extra Deck Cards
  • PSY-Framelord Omega - It allows you to return your banished cards into the Graveyard
  • Borreload Savage Dragon - Gives you negates and a big body. (Can be switched with any Extra Deck card you want)
  • Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons - A monster that is indestructible, and gains attack from damage. (Can be swithced with any Extra Deck card you want)
  • Armory Arm - It gives 1 monster 1000 attack and burst damage by equipping it. (Can be swithced with any Extra Deck card you want)
  • Borrelguard Dragon - Almost a generic Link monster. Allows you to resurrect a monster that was destroyed during the turn. It also can flip your Flip monsters or prevent 1 attack. Indestructible by card effects. (Technically optional, but highly recommended.)
  • Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax - Allows you to beat over any Special Summoned monsters. It also prevents you opponents from attacking your other monsters. It can't be targeted by card effects. (Technically optional, but highly recommended. Can be swapped with Borreload Dragon)
  • Borrelsword Dragon - Almost a generic Link monster. Allows you to attack twice during the Battle Phase. It also allows you to beat over almost any monster. Indestructible by battle. (Technically optional, but highly recommended. Can be swapped with Mekk-Knight Crusadia Avramax)
  • Subterror Behemoth Fiendess - Allows you dump a flip card to summon a monster in your hand in face-down defense position. It also searches any flip card in your deck or graveyard when a monster it points to is flipped.
  • Knightmare Phoenix - Almost a generic Link monster. Destroys 1 card in the backrow. (Technically optional)
  • Knightmare Cerberus - Almost a generic Link monster. Destroys 1 Special Summoned card in the Main Monster Zone. (Technically optional)
  • Pentestag - Almost a generic Link monster. Allows the card it points to inflict piercing damage. (Can be swithced with any Extra Deck card you want).
  • Proxy Dragon - Generic Link monster. Allows you to prevent card/battle destruction by destroying 1 card it points to instead. (Technically optional)
  • Puzzlomino, the Drop-n-Deleter - Almost a generic Link monster. It allows you to adjust the level of the Scapeghost token Special Summoned to its Link marker for Synchro plays (it can also happen with any monster revival that does not put it face-down). It can also destroy a monster card on your opponents card by destroying 1 monster card you control with the same level. (Technically optional, but highly recommended.)
  • Security Dragon - Generic Link monster. It allows you to bounce a monster your opponent controls once while it is co-linked. (Technically optional)
  • Beat Cop of the Underworld - Generic Link monster. It can help you protect one face-up card if you managed to activate its effect if you tribute a monster. (Can be swithced with any Extra Deck card you want)
  A problem with this deck is the initial setup of your field. Sometimes, your search can be negated by hand traps. You might also have cards that is not suitable for field setup. But if you managed to setup properly, they will have a hard time dealing with your field. Also, if your opponent clears your field, it can also be hard to recover your monsters. Replay Example: https://www.mediafire.com/file/acsms6anktf1g26/Hardest_Setup.yrp/file

deck_excerpt: This decks combine between Shianui, Zombie World, and Mayakashi.
deck_description: The main strategy of this archetype is to rapidly climb through the Synchro Summons, from Level 3 to 11, and then climb down again, by reviving one Synchro after the other. The lynchpin of this mechanic is the effect of "Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi". It can be easily Special Summoned by "Hajun, the Winged Mayakashi", enabling the first Synchro Summon. The said Synchro Monsters are side-unique and have 2 effects, following the pattern below: ● If your Synchro Monster whose original Level is [two Levels higher than its own original Level] is destroyed by battle or an opponent's card effect while this card is in your GY: You can banish 1 other Zombie monster from your GY, and if you do, Special Summon this card. ● If this card is Special Summoned from the GY: You can [...] The only exception to the first effect is "Gashadokuro, the Skeletal Mayakashi", a Level 11 monster that requires a Link monster to be destroyed, instead. The archetype in fact has a Link monster, the Link-2 "Yuki-Onna, the Ice Mayakashi", that cannot be targeted for attacks while pointing to a Synchro Monster and that halves the ATK/DEF of a monster when a Synchro Monster is destroyed by the opponent. The second Trigger Effect of the "Mayakashi" monsters range from immunity against destruction/effects to card destruction and Deck milling. They can be used by being preemptively Special Summoned from the Graveyard by generic effects such as "Book of Life", "Mezuki", and "Call of the Haunted", for example, or by "Mayakashi Metamorphosis". The two latter can be used to disrupt the opponent's plays, by Special Summoning the "Mayakashi" during their turn. Also, if their second effect is triggered by their own condition, they can be combined with "Shiranui" monsters, that can have their effects triggered when banished, especially "Shiranui Spiritmaster". “Yuki-Musume, the Ice Mayakashi” adds more versatility and consistency to the deck, as she makes it easier to quickly link summon “Yuki-Onna, the Ice Mayakashi” and continue climbing the Synchro ladder. In addition to that, her effect to send any Zombie of your choice from your deck to the GY once she’s special summoned from your hand or GY means that cards like “Doomking Balerdroch”, “Glow-Up Bloom”, and “Necroworld Banshee” are now more realistic options for the deck, and also allow a “Zombie World” engine to be more viable. “Mayakashi Winter” also helps with the OTK strategy by reducing the ATK of your opponent’s monsters, and it helps that multiple copies will stack on top of each other while on the field. Usually when you’re done climbing the Synchro ladder, you’re left with a “Dakki, the Graceful Mayakashi” on the field that’s not doing anything so you can use this card’s effect to send it to the GY to draw a new card.
